{
  "text": "A basic technique used to find an upper bounds for forb for a given matrix (or family) is standard induction, introduced in [CITATION_1] . Here, we show a known inequality bounding the growth of forb with respect to m. Let a k × ℓ (0,1)-matrix F be given. If A is such that A ∈ Avoid(m, F ) and |A| = forb(m, F ), then let us consider some row t of A. By permuting t to the top row and then permuting the columns, we get the following permutation of A:",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "30966170"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "30966170": {
      "title": "Forbidden configurations: Induction and linear algebra",
      "abstract": "Abstract Let a matrix be called simple if it is a (0, 1)-matrix with no repeated columns. We consider results of the form: if A is an m × n simple matrix with no submatrix which is a column permutation of F for all F in some specified set of matrices F , then n ≤ f(m). We obtain some results using induction and some results using linear algebra."
    }
  }
}